※※
# board-prep — Dark Factory rung 0 (onboarding), GitHub path

Idempotent, ASSISTED-MODE onboarding that prepares a repo + its GitHub Project for the
Dark Factory ladder. GENERIC: runs against the CALLER's repo (the run's working dir) and a
GitHub Project you pass by number. Pure bash + `gh`, deterministic, fail-closed — no LLM,
no budget.

WHY this exists (the researched gap): a GitHub Projects v2 **template** reproduces board
STRUCTURE (the Status single-select + its options, other custom fields, views) but it does
NOT carry — and no project copy/template ever can — the two things onboarding actually
needs wired per repo:
  • repo-scoped LABELS  (labels live on the repository, not the project), and
  • the AUTO-ADD workflow (explicitly excluded from copy/template; has no public API).
So this workflow fills exactly that gap: it creates the 9 lifecycle labels on the repo,
links the project to the repo, verifies the project carries the dark-factory field schema
(from the Skylence project template), and prints the two MANUAL UI steps the API can't do.

Two vocabularies it reconciles:
  • LABELS  (repo, what the ladder rungs key off):  data/labels.yaml — triaging · accepted ·
    ready-for-sky · in-progress · needs-review · approved · needs-fix · rejected · escalated
  • COLUMNS (project Status field, the human Kanban, from org project #1 "Skylence project
    template"):  Icebox · Backlog · Ready · Agent Running · Awaiting Review ·
    Revisions Requested · Done   (+ Priority / Size / Idea Stage / Bug Stage custom fields)
The label→column mapping lives in the `darkfactory-onboarding` skill and in the report.

  (skyway run board-prep --var project=<n> [--var owner=<org-or-user>] [--var repo=<owner/name>])
        │
        ▼
   ┌──────────────┐  bash + gh. Resolve OWNER/REPO (--var repo or `gh repo view`), require
   │  preflight   │  --var project=<n>, verify project access (needs gh `project` scope).
   └──────────────┘  Fail-closed: any missing → exit 1. Emits {owner,repo,project} JSON.
        │ depends_on (preflight)
        ├───────────────┬───────────────┐
        ▼               ▼               ▼
   ┌──────────┐   ┌──────────┐   ┌──────────────┐
   │  labels  │   │  link    │   │   fields     │  bash + gh, all idempotent / read-only:
   └──────────┘   └──────────┘   └──────────────┘  labels = `gh label create --force` ×9;
   create 9        `gh project    verify Status options + the custom fields exist on the
   lifecycle       link` the      linked project (advisory — never mutates the project).
   labels on       project to
   the repo        the repo
        └───────────────┴───────────────┘
                        │ depends_on [labels, link, fields], trigger_rule all_done
                        ▼
                 ┌──────────────┐  bash. Summarize what was done + print the 2 MANUAL UI
                 │   report     │  steps with no API: (1) enable Auto-add filtered to this
                 └──────────────┘  repo, (2) wire the label→Status column automation.

SAFETY:
  - Idempotent: `gh label create --force` upserts; re-linking an already-linked project is a no-op.
  - Read-only on the project's fields (the `fields` node only verifies; it never edits the schema).
  - Fail-closed: a missing --var project, an unresolvable repo, or no project access aborts at preflight.
  - Uses the run environment's ambient `gh` auth; needs the `project` scope for the project calls.
※※

⊕meta⊕
name = "board-prep"
description = "Dark Factory rung 0 (onboarding, GitHub): idempotently create the 9 lifecycle labels (data/labels.yaml) on the caller's repo, link a GitHub Project to the repo, verify the project carries the dark-factory field schema (Status: Icebox→Done plus Priority/Size/Idea Stage/Bug Stage, from the Skylence project template), and print the manual UI steps the GitHub API cannot do (auto-add workflow + label→Status automation). A project template carries board STRUCTURE but never repo labels or auto-add wiring — this fills that gap. Pure bash + gh, deterministic, fail-closed, idempotent. Fire via: skyway run board-prep --var project=<project-number> [--var owner=<org-or-user>] [--var repo=<owner/name>]"
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
⊕⊕

※preflight※
Step 1 — preflight. DETERMINISTIC bash + gh, no LLM. Resolve the target and fail-closed before
any mutation. OWNER/REPO come from --var (→ $SKY_OWNER / $SKY_REPO) or, when REPO is unset, from
`gh repo view` in the working dir; OWNER defaults to REPO's owner. PROJECT ($SKY_PROJECT, a
GitHub Project NUMBER) is REQUIRED. Project access is checked with `gh project view` (which needs
the `project` auth scope). Emits ONE JSON line {owner,repo,product} consumed downstream via jq.
{{var}} is NOT used — bash reads the $SKY_* env channel directly and shell-quotes every expansion.
※※

§preflight§
bash_file = "./scripts/preflight.sh"
§§

※labels※
Step 2 — labels. DETERMINISTIC bash + gh, no LLM. Create the 9 repo-scoped lifecycle labels from
data/labels.yaml on the target repo. `gh label create --force` is an idempotent UPSERT (creates, or
overwrites color/description if the label already exists), so re-runs are safe. Labels are the one
thing no project template can ever provide (they are repo-scoped). REPO comes from preflight's JSON.
※※

§labels§
depends_on = ["preflight"]
bash_file = "./scripts/labels.sh"
§§

※link※
Step 3 — link. DETERMINISTIC bash + gh, no LLM. Link the project to the repo so the board can pull
the repo's items. `gh project link` is idempotent in effect — an already-linked project is reported,
not treated as an error. OWNER/REPO/PROJECT come from preflight's JSON.
※※

§link§
depends_on = ["preflight"]
bash_file = "./scripts/link.sh"
§§

※fields※
Step 4 — fields. DETERMINISTIC bash + gh, no LLM. READ-ONLY verification: does the linked project
carry the dark-factory field schema from the Skylence project template? Reports any missing custom
field (Status / Priority / Size / Idea Stage / Bug Stage) and any missing Status COLUMN option
(Icebox … Done). It NEVER edits the project — creating/altering single-select fields is the
template's job; this only tells you whether the template was applied. grep is a substring check
(advisory). FL falls back to {} if the field-list call has no access.
※※

§fields§
depends_on = ["preflight"]
bash_file = "./scripts/fields.sh"
§§

※report※
Step 5 — report. DETERMINISTIC bash, no LLM. The single leaf — depends on labels+link+fields with
trigger_rule all_done so it always summarizes. Echoes each upstream node's output, then prints the
two MANUAL Projects-UI steps that have NO public API: (1) enable Auto-add filtered to this repo,
(2) wire the label→Status column automation (the mapping the ladder + the human board share).
※※

§report§
depends_on = ["labels", "link", "fields"]
trigger_rule = "all_done"
bash_file = "./scripts/report.sh"
§§
